@Tutorial(time: 20) {
    @Intro(title: "Evaluate the Typed AST") {
        With the typed AST in place from Tutorial 5, an evaluator
        becomes a recursive function that pattern-matches on
        `ExprSyntax`. Each kind has a closed structure â€” its operands
        and operator are addressable through the typed accessors â€”
        so the evaluator stays small and total.

        Along the way you will see ``CambiumCore/SyntaxTokenCursor/withTextUTF8(_:)``
        as the byte-level alternative to materializing literal text:
        an integer literal can be parsed straight from the token's
        UTF-8 bytes without any intermediate `String`.
    }

    @Section(title: "Domain types") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Cambium does not know what your language's *values* look
            like. The calculator's value type is a tagged union over
            integers and reals; the error type carries source ranges
            so the REPL can echo the offending position.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Define `CalculatorValue` and `CalculatorEvaluationError`.
                The error cases reuse Cambium's
                ``CambiumCore/TextRange`` so callers can render the
                error position against the source document the parser
                consumed.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorValue.swift", file: "06-eval-01-types.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "An entry point and per-kind dispatch") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            The evaluator opens the tree with `withRoot`, projects the
            root through `RootSyntax`, and then recurses through
            `ExprSyntax`'s union cases. Every case ultimately calls
            back into `evaluate(_:)`, so a single mutable evaluator
            instance can carry per-pass state â€” a counter, a cache,
            metadata sidecars (added in Chapter 3).
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Add `evaluateCalculatorTree(_:)` as the public entry
                point and a `CalculatorEvaluator` struct whose
                `evaluate(_:)` method dispatches on `ExprSyntax`. The
                kind-specific helpers are stubs for now; the next
                steps fill them in.

                Notice the evaluator opens `withRoot` and projects
                through `RootSyntax` exactly once â€” once we are inside
                `evaluate(_:)` the typed accessors traverse the green
                tree on demand.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorEvaluator.swift", file: "06-eval-02-entry.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Read literals through borrowed bytes") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Integer evaluation runs on every literal in every parse.
            Materializing each token's text as a `String` is wasteful
            when all we need is the digit bytes. ``CambiumASTSupport``'s
            token wrapper exposes ``CambiumCore/SyntaxTokenCursor/withTextUTF8(_:)``
            which hands the closure a borrowed
            `UnsafeBufferPointer<UInt8>` over the token's UTF-8 bytes
            â€” no copy, no `String` allocation on the happy path.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Add `evaluateInteger(_:)` and `evaluateReal(_:)`. The
                integer path runs `parseInt64` against the borrowed
                bytes; the real path falls back to `Double(_:)` (the
                stdlib has no from-bytes parser) but still avoids the
                `token.text` allocation on success.

                The error path materializes `token.text` for the
                diagnostic; that allocation is bounded to the literal,
                not the document.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorEvaluator.swift", file: "06-eval-03-literals.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Recurse into compound expressions") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            The remaining four cases â€” unary, group, round-call,
            binary â€” recurse into `evaluate(_:)` for their sub-
            expressions. The code stays close to the structure of the
            grammar because the typed accessors are kind-specific.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Fill in the four compound evaluators. Each one fetches
                its operand(s) through the typed accessor, recurses
                via `evaluate(_:)`, and combines the results with
                arithmetic that surfaces overflow / non-finite results
                as `CalculatorEvaluationError`.

                The binary evaluator delegates to two helpers
                (`evaluateIntegerBinary` and `evaluateRealBinary`)
                that switch over `CalculatorBinaryOperator`; the
                actual integer/real arithmetic is unrelated to
                Cambium and lives in a separate file in the sample.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorEvaluator.swift", file: "06-eval-04-recursive.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Assessments {
        @MultipleChoice {
            Why does the integer evaluator use
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxTokenCursor/withTextUTF8(_:)`` rather
            than `token.text`?

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                `withTextUTF8` is asynchronous and yields back to the
                runtime.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    `withTextUTF8` is synchronous. The advantage is
                    elsewhere.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: true) {
                It exposes the token's bytes through a borrowed buffer
                pointer, so a parser like `parseInt64` can run without
                allocating a `String` per literal.

                @Justification(reaction: "That's right") {
                    On the happy path the only allocations are
                    whatever your parser does. For an integer parser
                    that's zero allocations.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                `token.text` is not implemented for tokens whose kind
                is dynamic-text.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    `token.text` works for all token kinds â€” it
                    materializes the bytes through the resolver. The
                    issue is allocation cost, not availability.
                }
            }
        }

        @MultipleChoice {
            What does the evaluator gain from `ExprSyntax` being a
            tagged union rather than a free-form `SyntaxNodeHandle`?

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                A `~Copyable` constraint that prevents accidental
                tree retention.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    `ExprSyntax` is fully copyable. Ownership control
                    sits in the tree storage, not in the typed
                    overlay.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: true) {
                Exhaustive `switch` coverage. Adding a new expression
                kind is a compiler error in every consumer that
                pattern-matches on `ExprSyntax`.

                @Justification(reaction: "That's right") {
                    Exhaustiveness is the central reason to project a
                    typed overlay over the homogeneous CST. The
                    compiler enforces that every kind has a handler
                    everywhere.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                Direct mutation of expression children.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    Cambium trees are persistent. Editing happens via
                    `replacing(_:with:context:)`, which builds a new
                    tree.
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
